observations:
Based on Michael P. Staples' bio:
After spending time on YouTube, I notice that my child:
Becomes more curious and asks questions about the content they watched.
Sometimes imitates the behaviors or actions they saw in videos.
Can become distracted or unfocused if they watch YouTube for extended periods.
I'm concerned about:
Exposure to mature or inappropriate content.
The potential impact on their physical activity levels and outdoor playtime.
The possibility of cyberbullying or online harassment.
I've been surprised by:
How quickly my child can learn new skills or concepts from educational YouTube videos.
The creativity and imagination they display after watching videos that encourage DIY projects or arts and crafts.
The way they can connect with other children or families through YouTube content, fostering a sense of community and belonging.
concerns:
Yes, I have experienced concerns about the content on YouTube.
Examples:
I've seen videos featuring stereotypes and biased representations of certain groups, which I worry might influence my children's perceptions and attitudes.
I've come across channels that promote aggressive or violent behavior, which I don't want my children to emulate.
I've noticed some videos containing mild profanity or suggestive language, which I don't think is suitable for young children.
Specific channels or videos:
I don't recall specific channel names, but I've seen videos featuring cartoon characters engaging in violent or aggressive behavior.
I've also seen videos promoting unrealistic beauty standards or materialistic values, which I worry might negatively impact my children's self-esteem and values.

If they watch educational content, they actually pick up new facts and skills, which is great. But I do worry about screen time—sometimes it’s hard to get them to stop watching, and I’ve noticed they get cranky when I turn it off. I’ve also been surprised by how quickly they find new channels and trends. It’s tough to keep up with what they’re watching!"
concerns: Yes, I’ve definitely had concerns about some of the content. Even on YouTube Kids, I’ve come across videos with inappropriate language or themes that seem too mature. Sometimes, even seemingly innocent channels include stereotypes or behavior that I don’t want my child picking up. One time, my child was watching an animated video, and suddenly, it had violent or overly dramatic scenes that scared them. I’ve also noticed that some prank channels encourage mean-spirited behavior, which I don’t want them to think is okay. Now, I try to monitor their screen time more closely and set parental controls.
